**Geometric Interpretation**

Since $|z| = 1,$ $z$ lies on the unit circle in the complex plane.  Let $O$ be the origin, $A$ be the point $1,$ $B$ be the point $z,$ and $C$ be the point $z^2.$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, O;

O = (0,0);
A = (1,0);
B = dir(120);
C = dir(240);

draw(Circle(O,1));
draw(O--A);
draw(O--B);
draw(O--C);
draw(A--B--C--cycle);

label("$O$", O, SW);
label("$A$", A, SE);
label("$B$", B, N);
label("$C$", C, S);
label("$1$", (O + A)/2, S);
label("$z$", (O + B)/2, NW);
label("$z^2$", (O + C)/2, SW);
[/asy]

Then $|1 + z| = |OA + OB| = AB,$ $|1 - z| = |OA - OB| = BA,$ and $|z^2| = |OC| = 1.$  Thus,
\[|1 - z + z^2| = |BA + OC| = BC.\]Hence, we want to maximize $AB + BC.$

**Triangle Inequality**

By the Triangle Inequality, $AB + BC \ge AC.$  Equality occurs when $B$ lies on line segment $AC.$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, O;

O = (0,0);
A = (1,0);
B = (0.5,sqrt(3)/2);
C = (0.5,-sqrt(3)/2);

draw(Circle(O,1));
draw(O--A);
draw(O--B);
draw(O--C);
draw(A--B--C--cycle);

label("$O$", O, SW);
label("$A$", A, SE);
label("$B$", B, N);
label("$C$", C, S);
label("$1$", (O + A)/2, S);
label("$z$", (O + B)/2, NW);
label("$z^2$", (O + C)/2, SW);
[/asy]

**Finding the Maximum**

Since $z$ lies on the unit circle, $z$ can be written in the form $z = \operatorname{cis} \theta = \cos \theta + i \sin \theta.$  Then $z^2 = \operatorname{cis} 2 \theta = \cos 2 \theta + i \sin 2 \theta.$

We want $B$ to lie on line segment $AC,$ so $z$ and $z^2$ must be collinear with 1.  This means the angles $AOB$ and $BOC$ must add up to 180 degrees.  In other words, $\theta + 2 \theta = 180^\circ,$ so $\theta = 60^\circ.$

Then $z = \operatorname{cis} 60^\circ = \frac{1}{2} + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} i,$ and
\[z^2 = \operatorname{cis} 120^\circ = -\frac{1}{2} + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} i.\]Hence,
\[AB = \left| 1 + \frac{1}{2} + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} i \right| = \sqrt{\frac{9}{4} + \frac{3}{4}} = \sqrt{3},\]and
\[BC = \left| \frac{1}{2} + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} i - \left( -\frac{1}{2} + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} i \right) \right| = 1.\]Therefore, the maximum value is $AB + BC = \sqrt{3} + 1.$

**Answer:** $\boxed{\sqrt{3} + 1}$
